##Wenchuan County has to do more to heal its wounds than it did after the earthquake

Health insight

Functional introduction, understand the health professional news

* After the Han Dynasty closed the city, the folk psychological consultant began to intervene, for the first group of medical staff to be replaced to do psychological counseling. In early February, medical rescue teams across the country began bringing in psychiatrists.
* Sichuan earthquake, the front-line medical staff 15 days or so to rotate, or it will cause serious anxiety. But this time, some of the staff have been carrying it for more than a month.
* The caretakers are already regarded as heroes by society, which in turn reminds them that you are heroes, that you must not be timid, that you must not be afraid, and that even if you are, you must not be known.
* In the mid-term, more and more people in Wuhan are experiencing emotional crisis. Because death is so close, everyone falls into a state of fear of the unknown.
* Psychological intervention in the Han outbreak was harder than in the Wenchuan County earthquake. Because we're dealing with an ongoing fear of death, not a definitive disaster outcome.

After the city closure in Wuhan, civilian psychological counselors began to intervene, for the first group of medical personnel were removed to do psychological counseling. In early February, medical teams across the country began bringing in psychiatrists.

In the case of the Wenchuan County Earthquake, front-line medical staff had to rotate for about 15 days, which would have caused severe anxiety. But this time, some of the staff have been carrying it for more than a month.

The fact that health care workers have been treated as heroes by society, in turn, reminds them that you are heroes, that you can not be timid, that you can not be afraid, and that even if you are, you can not be known.

In the middle of the epidemic period, more and more people in Wuhan are experiencing emotional crisis. Because death is so close, everyone falls into a state of fear of the unknown.

Psychological intervention in Wuhan is harder than it was in Wenchuan County. Because we're dealing with an ongoing fear of death, not a definitive disaster outcome.

At 2:07 a.m. , Tang Wei's cell phone rang.

As one of the first psychologists in Zhejiang to support Wuhan, Tang Wei gave out his mobile phone number from the first day he entered the shelter and insisted on answering it 24 hours a day, but it was the first time someone had called.

Cut Open the cell phone, the phone is a weak girl, "you can give me secret? "

When the answer was yes, the girl sobbed quietly and soon developed into a wailing cry. About half an hour later, she began to tell her story.

The girl is 22 years old, is a nurse, half a month ago came to Wuhan, oneself sign up, belong to head a hot impulse type. After arriving in Wuhan, he was assigned to a shelter for patients with mild illness. When she first arrived, the girl was still fresh and not afraid. About a week later, she developed a fear. On the one hand, there were news reports of doctors dying of infection. On the other hand, she had to care for more than 200 confirmed patients every day, some of whom were fine yesterday, they transferred him out of here today.

Slowly, she began not to eat, sleep well, a closed eye is the picture in the shelter, drive also can not drive away. The day before the call, the girl saw on the news that more than 3,000 health care workers had been infected in Wuhan, with the infection rate approaching 10 percent. That number was the last straw, and the girl fell apart.

"I didn't know what to do, so I had to hold the phone and listen to her cry, " said Tang Wei, chief physician of the Psychiatric Department of Wenzhou Kangning Hospital Group, he has participated in the Wenchuan County earthquake, Wenzhou 723 bullet train accident, Lishui East mountain landslide and other large-scale disaster psychological assistance, rich experience. But that night, he did nothing but listen for three hours with his phone in his hand.

At dawn, he asked the girl, can you sleep for a while. The girl replied that she could sleep, and they just hung up. Before hanging up, Tang Wei said, "if you still can't sleep at night, call me and I will accompany you. "

"This is a common condition among the first-line medical staff in Wuhan. At first no one felt anything, but after a long time, physical fatigue and psychological fear have reached their limits, " Tang Wei told Jianwen at 8:00 pm, when the Wenchuan County earthquake struck, front-line medical staff must rotate for 15 days or so, otherwise it will cause serious anxiety. But this time, some of the medics have been carrying it for more than a month.

According to a recent survey conducted by the Management Research Center of Guangzhou Allibi Hospital, 85% of the frontline medical staff believed that the work load during the epidemic period was 1-2 times that of normal times, six percent said their workload was more than four times normal. Nearly 70% of health care workers sleep quality was affected, some health care workers OCD, such as see the faucet to wash their hands.

February 3, the National Health Commission held a press conference, the first mention of the epidemic prevention and Control Center of the importance of psychological intervention. On February 9, Tang Wei arrived in Wuhan with the Third Group of Zhejiang medical teams. This is the first time that an expert group on psychological crisis intervention and rescue has been set up in Zhejiang. Around the same time, medical teams across the country brought along their own psychologists. On Tang's mobile wechat, there is a growing army of psychologists from the country's medical team, now numbering 209.

Their mission is clear. First, to ensure the mental health of all medical personnel in the rescue team. To provide the patients in Wuhan with the help they can get.

Medical staff being "heroic" brings psychological hidden danger

Outside the official system, groups of volunteers, assembled on an ad hoc basis by private psychologists, stepped in earlier.

Xue Pengjun was "compiled" on New Year's Eve. That night, a psychiatrist at a local hospital in Wuhan called for help in the group, and more than 100 health care workers at his hospital were evacuated from the front line, in urgent need of psychological intervention.

Xue Pengjun was selected because of his qualification as a second-level state psychological consultant and his palliative care experience. The next day, she was given basic information about six medical staff members, including their current status and possible psychological problems, and the hospital had coordinated the time to ask her to call three people a day.

"Of the six people, almost all wrote about anxiety, insomnia, some expressed fear of death because of physical symptoms, and one girl from the 1990s wrote about seeing crowds of people afraid of riots. "

Li Meng, director of the Hubei Association of Psychological Counselors, was one of the first counselors to participate in the rescue of the epidemic. She joined a psychological support group of more than 200 people because it was the first organized group of private volunteers to be allowed to answer the hotline for Psychological Crisis Intervention in Wuhan.

The first call she got had something to do with the paramedics. A couple from another province came to her for help. Their son, a nurse at a hospital in Wuhan, had been wearing a protective suit for a week, wearing wet underwear every day when he took it off. These days they clearly feel that the son is not in the right mood, do not answer the phone, text messages are only a few words, communication is not smooth, the two elderly people simply driven mad.

According to the number they gave, Li added the boy's wechat account, but the boy did not want to talk to her, only a few simple responses every day "I just got off work" , "I'm very tired" , "I want to go to sleep first" . A few days later, the boy sent her a message saying he had been infected, tested positive for nucleic acid, and had been sent to the isolation ward.

But even then, he wouldn't say much. He once sent a message to Li Meng, to the effect that I take off a suit of protective clothing every day and have more than 20 procedures, you outsiders simply can not understand. That's the most he's ever typed.

"What he needs most is genuine company, both online and offline. But like us, we can't build that kind of trust with just our online friends. From the point of view of psychological assistance, I can't do it if he doesn't ask for help. This is the biggest problem we encountered in the early days. I have a heart, but I can't exert myself,"Li Mengxiang said.

This awkwardness exists on a much larger scale. Tang Wei once contacted a female doctor who was one of the first to come to Wuhan for support. According to her account, at night in the medical team's station, people could often be heard yelling, crying and even strange laughter. These doctors are more willing to face stress alone than to seek help from a psychologist. Tang Wei thinks, this backside, it is a kind of dangerous"be heroic turn"signal.

"especially those who come from other places to help. Before they leave, there are going-away ceremonies all over the place. Those who wear big red flowers on their chest are already regarded as heroes by the society. This in turn reminds them that you are heroes. You must not be timid, you must not be afraid, and even if you do, you must not be known. "

The Empty Nester has been holding it in for so long that the string in his heart is about to snap

Because it is an open help line, in addition to medical staff, Li Meng is more faced with ordinary Wuhan residents. Li Meng told Jianwen at eight o'clock that early phone calls from people were mostly based on questions, such as how serious the disease was, how long the quarantine would last, and when the epidemic would end. There were no emotional problems. But one day in mid-february, she felt the wind change.

That morning, she answered five hotlines, all of them empty nesters who lived in Wuhan. This vulnerable group, which lacks the support of family relationship, is the first to show the characteristics of "suspicious Crown" .

A 57-year-old man, 10 days ago to the drug store to buy a drug, since never out. One day, he saw the news on TV that someone in Henan had been infected with a new coronavirus by buying Shuanghuanglian from a pharmacy. He suspected that he had also contracted the disease and could not sleep all night. That night, he had a slight tickle in his throat and was hot all over. The "new crown" symptoms he had seen on the news bore witness to them. He thought he was going to die soon. The next morning, the old man couldn't wait to call the hotline.

"In the face of such an old man, the first thing we should do is to make sure that he is healthy and has a fever and cough. Two, make sure he's safe, get enough food. In general, people who can call psychological hotlines for help have no problems in these areas. Their problem is that they've been holding it in for so long that it's starting to snap."

The consequences of breaking the string would be catastrophic. On February 16, Yang Yuanyun, who lives in Hannan District, Wuhan, climbed a wall outside his home alone and hanged himself in an abandoned factory building because he suspected he had new pneumonia. He wrote in a suicide note to his family: The epidemic was a joke to him, but he accepted it.

But even to death, Yang Yuanyun also don't know if he really got sick. He told community workers that he struggled with illness every day and could not eat or sleep well. For Fear of infecting his family, he pleaded, if it wasn't this disease, I should be in the hospital. The response: The beds are tight, the service is not available.

"whether he has it or not, the fact that he has initiated a community-based approach to help suggests that the tragedy could have been prevented with appropriate psychological intervention, " hotline volunteer Li Juan told the 8:00 News, she also received a number of calls from suspected patients, most of whom turned out not to be infected after the fact, but because the deaths were so close together, all of whom were unconsciously plunged into fear of the unknown.

She had once encountered a supplicant on the platform. When she picked up the phone, she began with the usual line: Hello, this is the so and so platform's outbreak hotline. I'm Li Juan, the consultant. What's your question?

I'm just wondering if I have this disease, you said. You said this was an outbreak hotline. Doesn't that mean that the people calling this number are all sick.

For the next 10 minutes or so, the man railed on about everything from his little opening line to the inaction of the Wuhan Municipal Government to the topic of why humans eat game and balance of nature. Finally, without waiting for Li Juan to respond, he hung up.

"I feel like I helped him in those 10-plus hours, or at least got him to say what he was holding back. "

Li Juan said that this was a large group of people, especially as the epidemic progressed and the home quarantine continued for longer and longer periods, and she clearly felt the emotions on the other end of the phone getting more intense. To ensure the health of the counselors themselves, the platform limits each person to five calls a day, each for no more than 25 minutes. "Even if it's just one day at a time, the platform is allowed. "

But Tang Wei apparently did not leave such a space for himself. The rihai shelter he serves is the largest shelter hospital in Wuhan, with a total of 4,500 beds. He went to the shelter three times and, through a simple conversation, screened the patients and medical staff he would like to focus on, after returning to the hotel is 24 hours to answer the phone or wechat video, every call is a negative mood of the heap.

"I now do push-ups three times a day, one in the morning, one in the middle of the night, 30-40 at a time, to exhaust myself and then take a hot bath. Otherwise I can't relax, and I'll get sick, " Tang told Jianwen at 8:00, since his departure on February 9, he has worked continuously for 17 days and lost 9 Jin.

All that's left is the sound

Problems keep popping up.

For example, Li Meng received a phone call a few days ago from an old man in his 70s. He was in a good mood and could have a drink at home. This time, he called the community to ask for a mask. The community staff were busy with other trifles and were impolite in answering him. The old man felt a fire in his chest. He and Li Meng complained, "How can they talk to me like that? They don't respect me at all. "

Tang Wei also began to be troubled by things beyond these duties. He was trying to comfort a patient in a shelter, a middle-aged woman who had just been diagnosed and was forcibly brought to the shelter hospital by the community because of mild symptoms. She did agree with the government's policies, but when she left, her son was left alone, and eating became her biggest problem. She questioned Tang Wei, "you told me not to worry, not to worry, then you go to my home to send the child rice OK. "

In the face of this major emergency, all Wuhan residents seem to understand the government's intentions, stoically sacrificed their freedom. On the other hand, they do get caught up in real life situations, where things that normally seem too small for a city to shut down suddenly become a matter of life and death.

"This is a very special point of this epidemic, where we are more often in a role between a psychologist and a social worker, and in addition to helping to relax, we are also helping to empower them to solve real problems. For example, tell them how to buy food online, and help them find out who the grid operator in the community is. You have to prepare these information materials to appease him,"Li said.

The other dilemma has to do with segregation. The inability to communicate face-to-face weakens the precision of the intervention, as all the counsellors interviewed spoke of without exception.

Tang Wei once received a phone call. The first thing the other party said was "I don't want to live, I want to kill myself. " He was immediately scared out of his skin because he didn't know what situation the other party was in, lying in bed at home, making jokes, or standing on the roof of a 30th floor building. Fortunately, it turned out to be a false alarm, because a teenager can not go out, naively thought, go out is killed by the virus, at home is suffocated by himself, I might as well go out "suicide" .

"This has never happened before, even in the case of the Wenchuan County earthquake, we sat face-to-face with the person asking for help. I had to judge his emotional state from his movements, his expression, his reaction to the environment. But now all that is left is his voice, which poses a great challenge to the psychologist. "

Another unavoidable point is that psychological intervention often requires two people to establish trust first. In daily life, the psychologist and the patient face-to-face Communication About 5-10 times, each time about an hour, it is possible to find that valuable connection, so as to build trust relationships, successful completion of treatment. This is almost impossible during an epidemic.

Li, who was also involved in the first-line rescue of the Wenchuan County earthquake, also found the psychological intervention of the Wuhan outbreak more difficult.

"Wenchuan County was already there, and faced with a very disastrous outcome, what are we going to do. For example, a school collapses, all the children are gone, the parents'hearts are in agony, this is clear to us, and the disaster is over, it can not be worse. But Wuhan is different, all people are in the fear of death, "No one knows will not get better, when good. "

Grief Intervention for the family members of the deceased patients

But the reality is that the test is far from over.

According to the experience of large-scale disaster psychological rescue in the past, the fear of death will soon pass away, and only death itself will leave eternal damage, Tang said. "What we did in Wenchuan County was a grief intervention, " he said. "It's not being done, it's being focused on the front-line staff, it's not being seen the psychological needs of the families of the dead. "

He mentioned a news story from the past few days. A 6-year-old boy lives with his grandfather in Shiyan, Hubei Province. The last time a volunteer came to take his temperature, he found his grandfather dead at home. The poor boy had been guarding the body for several days because he had listened to his grandfather's words, "there is a virus outside, you can't go out. " He was already a little wooden when he was found. "This is a classic case of Grief Intervention. If you don't intervene, you're more likely to develop post-traumatic stress disorder, which we call PTSD. "

A few days ago, Tang said, the Hangzhou Psychological Association has opened two hotlines, all the way to Hubei, all the way to Wuhan, to answer the phone calls of the families of the dead patients. In his view, this group faces at least two kinds of pressure, one is that someone in the family has been diagnosed with death, meaning that the family must be isolated, they also face death threats. Second, at this stage, the new crown death of patients will be directly dragged to the funeral home cremation, relatives did not prepare funeral matters, this for the traditional ethics of the Chinese people, it is also a big blow.

Xue and the team behind her have been aware of this phenomenon for a long time, and have been involved in the palliative care itself, giving them more leverage and resources. But until now, the project has been a long way off, says Xue. In fact, the in house training has been done, but there's only one thing people don't quite grasp -- the Harvard effect.

"grief intervention is very different from general psychological assistance, because it involves specific death, so we are very afraid that it will cause secondary injury to those who ask for help, " Xue told the eight-point health news. The two most important principles of grief intervention are: "But if you do it online, almost both of these principles will be broken. "

Tang Wei tried to solve the problem. He contacted the two-way hotline of the Hangzhou Psychological Association, hoping to reach a model of front-and-back cooperation, in which Hangzhou staff answer the hotline at the rear and screen out the more serious cases, he sought the possibility of a face-to-face intervention in Wuhan.

But at the moment, there are too many uncertainties, such as whether he will be allowed to leave the hotel and whether the other community will let him in. He believes these problems can be solved with the support of his superiors, so he wants the media to come in and help, if possible.

"The people of Wuhan are too bitter. We should do whatever we can. "
